<HL>
   E-Systems Inc. Pleads
   Guilty to Fraud; Firm
   To Pay $4.6 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
08/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   ESY
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- E-Systems Inc. pleaded guilty to charges that it
falsified test results and defrauded the U.S. government on
contracts for Army field radios. It agreed to pay $4.6
million to settle civil and criminal charges.
   An E-Systems spokesman said the settlement will allow the
electronic systems and products company to continue doing
business with the U.S. government. "All of our problems have
been cleared up," he said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   E-Systems said it will pay a $2 million fine and $1.8
million in restitution to settle criminal charges filed in a
Tampa, Fla., federal court as well as $850,000 to settle
civil charges brought by the Department of Justice. As part
of the plea agreement, E-Systems said it will drop its
pending $38 million lawsuit against the federal government.
   E-Systems took an $8.6 million write-off against its
second-quarter earnings in anticipation of the guilty plea,
the spokesman said.
   The tactical field radios were supplied to the Army by
E-Systems through its Memcor division, which has since been
discontinued. The indictment charged that E-Systems and
others falsified performance records of the radios and
concealed repairs and defects.
   This month, three former Memcor managers and a former
supervisor were charged by a federal grand jury with
falsifying records and test results to conceal failures and
defects in radios supplied to the U.S. Army.
   A production supervisor, Sadonna S. Hobbs, was convicted
Jan. 31 of perjury relating to denials of her activity in
connection with suits filed by E-Systems before the Armed
Services Board of Contract Appeals. She is serving a 16-month
federal prison term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900828-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900828-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Tax Revolt Revs Up
</HL>
<DATE>
08/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<LP>
   Anti-tax ballot measures will be voted on in at least
eight states this November, the most since 1980. The large
number of initiatives is explained in part by a Commerce
Department report. It showed that state tax collections in
1989 were up 7.5% overall from the year before, well above
inflation. The largest gains were in Oregon and California,
up 22.5% and 14.2% respectively. Both have anti-tax votes
scheduled.
   In California, local officials have recently circumvented
Proposition 13's tax cap by passing special taxes and fees
earmarked for a specific purpose. One proposed amendment
requires a two-thirds vote of the people for such changes.
The state Legislature also would be barred from raising taxes
without a vote of the people unless two-thirds of the
lawmakers approved. California voters approved an earmarked
gasoline tax in June, but by only 52% of the vote despite the
fact that the entire political establishment endorsed it.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Oregon has two initiatives on the ballot -- one to cap
property taxes and another to allow a tax credit of up to
$2,500 for parents sending their children to a private
school. Poor families who don't pay income tax would receive
a payment from the state, but since the state now spends
close to $6,000 on each public-school student it should save
money overall.
   Massachusetts is the only state in the nation to have
raised its taxes three years in a row. An initiative by
Citizens for Limited Taxation would repeal a 15% state
income-tax increase and all other taxes adopted after August
1989. State officials are already warning that voter approval
will mean cuts in police and fire protection. CLT leaders say
such scare tactics are akin to telling a man who has to lose
five pounds that he will have to cut off his arm instead of
going on a diet.
   Sales taxes often disproportionately hurt the poor, and
Utah tax groups are sponsoring an initiative to exempt all
food items from the state sales tax. Unless a court throws
two efforts off the ballot, Oklahomans will vote on two
initiatives to repeal an education-related tax hike and to
require that all new taxes be approved by a three-fourths
vote of the Legislature or a vote of the people.
   All the initiative sponsors had to run a gauntlet of
dubious legal challenges. In Illinois, proponents of a
measure to mandate a 60% vote in the Legislature to raise
taxes turned in more than 480,000 signatures, double what was
needed. After ballot certification, a circuit-court judge
rejected a constitutional challenge to it. Then last week,
the Illinois Supreme Court threw it off the ballot on the
grounds that it was not confined to changing the operations
of the Legislature.
   However, the overwhelming public support for the measure
has already forced both the Republican and Democratic
candidates for governor into an anti-tax corner. Within a day
of the court's ruling, both pledged they will not sign any
tax increase that doesn't meet the requirements of the
proposed amendment.
   All of the initiatives lead in the polls, but the barrage
of ads from the financially well-heeled special interests
hasn't started yet. Even so, the large number of initiatives
this year should serve as a message to both President Bush
and Congress that voter resentment over high taxes has by no
means dissipated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900828-0046
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900828-0046.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Buy-Backs Begun,
   Extended Amid
   Market Decline
   ----
   By Peter Pae
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   GRO LIZC PIZA SMCA HAS INTC NLC PHSY DBRN JBM FCHT BLTA
</CO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A steady decline in stock market prices since
the Middle East crisis began has led a number of companies to
start or extend stock repurchase programs hoping to snatch
their own shares at bargain prices.
   The companies believe the buy-backs will bolster the value
of the stocks in a stock market that has been battered by
Mideast events and investor fears of a recession.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But some companies that had announced buy-back programs
stayed away yesterday because of the market rally.
   Russell Banks, chief executive officer of Grow Group Inc.,
a New York-based chemical concern, said the board approved a
750,000-share buy-back in response to the market drop, but no
shares had been purchased because of the rally. The shares
closed yesterday at $7.50, up 37.5 cents, in New York Stock
Exchange composite trading; in July, they traded as high as
$10.
   Nevertheless, companies continued to take advantage of
deflated prices yesterday. Liz Claiborne Inc., a New York
apparel retailer, expanded its buy-back and National Pizza
Co., a fast-food chain based in Pittsburg, Kan., said
yesterday it would begin one.
   "We think it's a good use of our available cash," said Sam
Miller, chief financial officer for Liz Claiborne, which is
planning to buy back as much as an additional $50 million in
stock. "This should improve our earnings per share and
improve the stock price for our remaining shareholders."
   Liz Claiborne closed at $27.50 yesterday, up $1.75, in
national over-the-counter trading. Before the market
rebounded yesterday, Liz Claiborne stock closed at $25.75 a
share Friday, down from $30.75 a share Aug. 1, the day before
Iraq invaded Kuwait.
   Since Aug. 1, the Dow Jones Industrial Average had
declined 366 points before rebounding Monday.
   National Pizza also took advantage of deflated prices to
initiate its buy-back and in turn watch its stock rise
yesterday. In national over-the-counter trading, National
Pizza closed at $17.75, up from $17 a share Friday, but still
down from $21 a share on Aug. 1.
   "At recent price levels our common stock represents an
excellent investment," said Gene Bicknell, chief executive of
National Pizza, which is planning to repurchase as many as
one million shares, or 7.1% of its common outstanding.
   Liz Claiborne and National Pizza join more than 50
companies that have announced repurchase programs in the last
week.
   Among others, A.O. Smith Corp., a maker of auto, truck and
farm equipment, dusted off its 1987 authorization last week,
to repurchase $7.5 million in stocks while Hasbro Inc., a
Pawtucket, R.I., toymaker, said its board approved the
buy-back of as many as three million shares.
   Intel Corp., citing the market's "rapid retreat" and an
opportunity to buy back shares at "attractive levels,"
announced Aug. 23 that it would buy back 20 million shares.
   Since the announcement, Intel stock rose to $36.25 a share
at close of national over-the-counter trading yesterday. That
was up from $32.125 a share before the announcement, but
still down from $42.50 a share Aug. 1.
   Of course not all companies have the financial wherewithal
to take advantage of deflated stock prices. "Not everyone has
the flexibility to do it," said Liz Claiborne's Mr. Miller.
   Other companies that are extending or starting buy-back
programs include Nalco Chemical Co., Naperville, Ill. (one
million additional shares); PacificCare Health Systems Inc.,
Cypress, Calif. (500,000 shares); and Dress Barn Inc.,
Stamford, Conn. (two million shares)
   Yesterday, Jan Bell Marketing Inc., a Sunrise, Fla.,
designer and maker of jewelry, said it will buy back as much
as 10% of the 22.6 million shares outstanding, while First
Chattanooga Financial Corp., a thrift holding company in
Chattanooga, Tenn., said its board approved spending an
additional $2.5 million on top of $1.5 million to repurchase
stock. Blount Inc., a manufacturing and construction concern,
said it also plans to buy back as many as 300,000 Class A
common shares, or 4% of shares outstanding.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   GROW GROUP Inc. plans to buy back 250,000 of its shares.
The number of shares was overstated in yesterday's edition.
   (WSJ Aug. 29, 1990)
