<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/28/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS AND BONDS soared and oil prices plummeted on the
prospect of a peaceful solution to the Mideast crisis. The
Dow Jones industrials leaped 78.71 points, this year's
biggest gain, to 2611.63. Long-term Treasury bonds jumped
more than 1 1/2 points, bringing their yield back under 9%.
Crude prices sank as much as $4 a barrel, their sharpest drop
on record. Early Tuesday in Vienna, OPEC ministers
tentatively endorsed some members' moves to boost output.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices plunged about $27 an ounce in their sharpest
one-day decline in more than seven years. Silver and platinum
prices also sank. The recent Persian Gulf turmoil has
generated only a modest increase in investor interest in gold
in the U.S.
   ---
   Tokyo stocks posted strong gains amid a firmer yen, a
healthier bond market and an absence of bad Mideast news. The
Nikkei index jumped 976 points Monday to 25141.76, then rose
a further 518.52 Tuesday morning.
   ---
   Many banks tightened their lending standards further in
recent months, largely out of concern over the economy and
the state of certain industries, a Fed survey found.
Medium-sized firms felt the worst pinch. The report could
help support an easing by the Fed of interest rates.
   ---
   Consumer spending grew 0.5% in July, as personal income
rose 0.6%. But fears about the economy may restrain purchases
in the months ahead.
   ---
   A tobacco antitrust award against Brown &amp; Williamson was
overturned. Brooke Group, formerly Liggett, had won the
$148.8 million verdict.
   ---
   Former Guinness PLC Chairman Ernest Saunders was convicted
of conspiring to inflate the firm's stock price to help its
$4.91 billion bid to take over Distillers Co. in 1986. Three
co-defendants were also convicted in the case, which could
boost the reputation of British financial regulators.
   ---
   An insider-trading ruling that the government claims could
hinder prosecutions will get a rare review by a full federal
appeals court.
   ---
   Stock buy-back programs are being launched or extended by
many companies that hope to snatch their own shares at
bargain prices.
   ---
   Investors seeking arbitration of disputes with brokers
will have to pay higher fees to launch their claims. The NASD
has already imposed the increases, and the Big Board is
expected to follow suit within weeks.
   ---
   General Motors plans to triple the number of its
U.S.-built cars with air bags as standard equipment. GM has
trailed its U.S. rivals in this area.
   ---
   Merrill Lynch will get $17.5 million from its insurers
under a settlement of suits brought by the firm's
shareholders on its behalf. The case involved trading and
investment losses.
   ---
   Tracor Holdings proposed to restructure $730 million of
its debt and said it may seek protection from creditors if
the plan isn't approved.
   ---
   The IMF may lend more money to Brazil and other developing
nations that import oil, a Treasury aide said.
   ---
   General Cinema posted a 78% drop in profit for the quarter
that ended in July. The theater operator and retailer cited
lower movie attendance and reduced interest income.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 160,150,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2611.63, up 78.71; transportation 908.03, up 38.32; utilities
194.42, up 3.46.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3326.27, up
48.63.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.16, off 1.68;
spot index 132.23, off 1.95.
   Dollar: 144.25 yen, off 2.45; 1.5510 marks, off 0.0095.
</TEXT>
